replies.bodyText:
If this is the only scenario, my suggestion is moving the logic to following check in JobDispatcher. It checks whether we can determine a job is already stopped or not. It is also the right time that we check whether the instance assigned with tasks are gone or not. If it is gone, we can mark it as DROPPED.
public static boolean checkJobStopped(JobContext jobContext) {
for (int partition : jobContext.getPartitionSet()) {
TaskPartitionState taskState = jobContext.getPartitionState(partition);
if (taskState == TaskPartitionState.RUNNING) {
return false;
}
}
return true;
}

